## Phase 3 — Canvas & Rendering

**Step 11: Static Node Card Renderer**

Before any layout engine, get individual node cards rendering correctly. Each kind has its own visual template:
- Interface/Type card: header with name and kind badge, then a row per field showing name, type, and modifiers
- Enum card: header, then a compact list of values
- Class card: header, property rows, then a divider, then method rows
- Table card: header with table name, column rows with PK/FK/type badges
- Method node: compact single-block showing signature

**Step 12: Edge Renderer**

Draw edges between cards as curved or straight lines with arrowheads. Different edge kinds get different visual treatments — extends is a hollow arrow, references is a solid arrow, foreign-key is a dashed line, implements is a dotted line. Where multiple edges go to the same target, fan them out slightly so they don't stack on top of each other.

**Step 13: Static Auto-Layout (no physics yet)**

Before adding drag and force, implement a simple deterministic layout. Group nodes by kind into columns or clusters — enums on one side, interfaces in the center, tables on another side, methods near their parent class. Use a grid within each group with consistent spacing. This gives a readable starting position before the user interacts.

**Step 14: Force-Directed Layout**

Layer a spring physics simulation on top of the static layout. Connected nodes attract, all nodes repel each other, edges act as springs. The simulation runs for a fixed number of ticks on first load to settle the graph, then pauses. The user can trigger re-layout at any time. Important: nodes the user has manually dragged stay pinned and don't get moved by the simulation.

**Step 15: Zoom & Pan**

Wrap the canvas in a viewport transform. Scroll wheel zooms in/out centered on the cursor. Click and drag on empty canvas pans. Add zoom controls (+ / - / reset) in the corner. The viewport transform is just a scale + translate applied to the root SVG group — all node positions stay in graph coordinates.

**Step 16: Node Drag**

Each node card is draggable. On drag start, pin the node so the force simulation ignores it. On drag end, keep the node pinned at its new position. This lets users manually clean up the layout.

